Minz sat in silence. Staring out across the ocean.<br>
<br>
Things had bee going so well. The meeting was going smoothly. Business was getting done.<br>
<br>
He was proud that they were growing. Not quickly. But steadily. Vallden and Nadilaa brought their numbers up to 18. Small, but a solid group. He wasn't concerned about their size. Rather concerned about their character. Several petitioners had actually been turned away.<br>
<br>
And then he showed up.<br>
<br>
Windam sounded the first alarm, and Minz ran out onto the stage. There he was...Xareth<br>
<br>
Grinning wickedly.<br>
<br>
Tossing verbal barbs at Windam.<br>
<br>
Minz hissed as he saw the drow. Clenching his teeth, steeling himself for what he knew he had to do. Offer this one his aid. Aid in finding a cure to the curse that lay like a dead weight on Silverstarr and Xareth.<br>
<br>
The exchange was short and pointed (sorry, I forgot to log it)<br>
<br>
Minz was shocked at the foolhardiness of Xar when he heard he actually killed Michae, the one who put the curse on them. His hope had been to wheedle the cure from him. But that hope now lay in ashes.<br>
<br>
Their yelling began to attract a crowd. (actually a few came to watch. The theater turned out to be a great venue) A few warriors eager to see a brawl sat on the earth. A halfling thief scurried about, clearly looking for easy targets, and a somber Tier 'Dal cleric named Tenzein, hovered off to the side (a GM...way cool!! Afterwards she told us how impressed she was with our RP. Too much fun!!)<br>
<br>
His attempt to cajole Xareth into accepting his help had disintegrated into pointless and viscous banter. The Dragons seethed behind him. Young Vallden stood at Xareth's back, wrapped in the shadows, his rapier poised at the drow's neck. Urging me to give him the word.<br>
<br>
Finally, he could stand no more. &quot;ENOUGH!!&quot; he shouted. Eyes snapped away from the drow onto him. Few had ever seen him raise his voice. Xareth grinned evilly. Taking a deep labored breath, he made one final attempt, &quot;Xareth,&quot; he said through gritted teeth. &quot;Accept our help or accept our venom.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Your venom?&quot; he laughed. &quot;I'll tell you what. Face me. Here and now. Alone. Should you win, I will give you proof that the wench Silverstarr is alive and well.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;And if I do not?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Should you lose, you will provide your services to me for a target of my choosing.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;NO Minz!! Don't?&quot; Saludin and others called out.<br>
<br>
&quot;Done&quot; was the only reply give, as I slipped behind him, plunging my spear into his back.<br>
<br>
(OK, bad choice here. We were dueling away, having a ball, when the dumbass guard strode by. Jumping on Xareth. D'OOOHH!!! So what do I do?? Backstab the guard of course, yelling at Xar to run. /bonk self. Well I was toasted. But Tenzein gave me a full GM res. I presume that is better than a normal one. No idea really. But I was really psyched. This was when she complimented us. Also, this untimely death filled the &quot;Naked Minz&quot; requirement, making it an Official OED event. After looting, we moved to the arena. Now back to our regularly scheduled program already in progress.)<br>
<br>
One final slash, I saw it coming, but was too fatigued to parry it. Falling to the ground. The weight of the loss sinking in. I would have to kill a mark for Xareth.<br>
<br>
The ocean roared loudly. I sighing heavily, I asked the same question again, &quot;what have I done?&quot;<br>
