The Prophet and The Dragons, Part 2 (*RP*)<br>
-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
*ooc* I'm going to try and keep this whole thing in one thread, so as to make it easier to go back and re-read anything missed. Also, I thought this would only be 2 parts, but it seems there will have to be at least a third part. *shrug* Well, it was a fairly long session. Oh, and once again, I reiterate - I have taken some &quot;poetic license&quot; with the events. What I mean by that is that some comments and actions were changed in terms of the order they were said so as to make for a better story. In any event, on with part 2.<br>
<br>
======================================<br>
<br>
The prophet had paused to let them voice their boasts and then said, &quot;And then I will see to the pretty little bard 10 times over.&quot;<br>
<br>
The silence was deafening as the implications sank in. Several members prayed to their puny gods while others whispered amongst themselves.<br>
<br>
&quot;...to protect our sister...then again...&quot;<br>
<br>
The half-breed glared at the prophet and said, &quot;Be gone from this place Drow!&quot;<br>
<br>
The prophet chuckled with evil glee as he remembered a task he had been putting off for a time. Now was definitely the perfect time.<br>
<br>
&quot;I will,&quot; the prophet said still smiling. &quot;For I have business with that wigmaker outside of town. I have some pretty fresh hair to sell him.&quot;<br>
<br>
The young prophet smirked devilishly as he held up some strands of the bard's hair. Then they all began to speak at once.<br>
<br>
&quot;Priest... your fellow just came and swore to our sister's well being.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Yeah...scum like you shouldn't be allowed around here.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Know this, Pravdameer. If any harm befalls her, I will personally destroy you and others who have caused it.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;You all pray I will lock and load.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Pravdameer, it seems no one is with you... why is that?&quot;<br>
&quot;You all are so alike.&quot;<br>
<br>
The young priest basked in the waves of hatred that washed over him, while their half-breed leader shook with rage and suddenly shouted out, &quot;BE GONE!!!&quot;<br>
<br>
As he turned to leave he heard the bard bearing the red shield mumble, &quot;I think... I think this one serves no good purpose.&quot; He considered turning back to toy with them some more when he heard a shout of, &quot;Run like the fool that you are!&quot;<br>
<br>
That definitely settled it. He went back and said, &quot;Oh, I serve a good purpose indeed little bard.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;No GOOD purpose,&quot; The bard said. &quot;You swear to harm our sister, while your brother swears you serve him. I think you talk too much priest, and have no power.&quot;<br>
<br>
The patsy then turned an icy glare upon the young prophet and said, &quot;My patience wears thin, Pravdameer. Consider yourself fortunate, today Tier'dal. Out of respect for Minz I will not take your wretched life&quot;<br>
<br>
The one who had accused the priest of being a fool (Atoxus said her name was Windam) then called out, &quot;Ah I am glad Windi taught me of your ways - or do you remember her?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I do - and she knows nothing of my ways,&quot; the prophet replied.<br>
<br>
&quot;Oh but she does. She knows more then you care to know&quot;<br>
<br>
Another, whom Atoxus named as Saludin, said, &quot;Pravdameer, I have a question for you. Why did you kidnapped Silver to find a cure? Why didn't you tell us that you wanted to help us...like 'normal' people would?&quot;<br>
<br>
Before the young priest had a chance to ridicule their questions, the half-breed said, &quot;Leave him be. No good will come of this.&quot;<br>
<br>
Then the one Atoxus said was named Ascrida spit in his face for the slurs he had made upon the Dragons as well as his actions while the bard with the red shield tried to cover his fury by laughing at Pravdameer.<br>
<br>
The young prophet saw through it all. He chuckled at them all as they came after to hurl more insults and threats as their hatred began to consume them. &quot;You fools tell me to leave, and then you come chasing after me like a pack of lost puppies. Isn't that so sweet.&quot; He then showed how unmoved he was by their words by yawning widely in their faces.<br>
<br>
&quot;Ah, but you don't know what 'sweet' is,&quot; the one named Windam said.<br>
<br>
&quot;Bah, I think this one would serve us like he serves Xareth,&quot; said the bard with that foolish looking red shield.<br>
<br>
Then the paladin, Quezex, began to tighten the grip on his sword and said, &quot;So how about it? Want to go to your bastard god tonight?&quot; <br>
